[ctns_make id='algDefLogicS1']

    [ctns_problem_height]
        360
    [/ctns_problem_height]

    [ctns_problem_width]
        600
    [/ctns_problem_width]

    [ctns_front]
Logic Statements
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:80%;']
<div>
<div style='float:left;text-align:right'>
statement:<br/>
contrapositive:<br/>
converse:<br/>
inverse:
</div>
<div>
$$p \implies q$$<br/>
$$\neg q \implies \neg p$$<br/>
$$q \implies p$$<br/>
$$\neg p \implies \neg q$$
</div>
</div>
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
For well-formed formulas P and Q, --
Let a statement read as -- P implies Q, --
The contrapositive to this statement reads negative Q implies negative P, --
the converse to this statements reads Q implies P, --
And finally, the inverse to this statement reads negative P implies negative Q.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]

